OLIANSKY'S 'COMPETITION'
description: THE key characters in ''The Competition'' are pianists, but somehow all the music for this love story seems to be coming from a string section. The movie isn't truly softhearted; if anything, it works very, very hard to be taken seriously. But it has a sentimental streak you could drive a truck through, and that turns out to be its most endearing feature. The nicest thing this movie offers is the spectacle of two young blue-eyed prodigies falling prettily in love. It needn't have strained for much more.

description: When the birds flew south for the winter this year, I can't help but imagine, they'd had advance word of what the Christmas movies would be like. And I'll bet the ones flapping hardest to get away were those who knew about ''Tribute.'' There is maudlin, then there is more maudlin and then there is this, a hair-raisingly soggy movie about a fellow, who, as one of the other characters describes him, is ''just about the most charming man I've ever met.'' Whoever says this is absolutely out of his or her mind.

'TELL ME A RIDDLE,' AGED PAIR'S LOVE STORY
description: IF you're suffering from holiday depression, rest assured that somebody out there understands: ''Tell Me a Riddle'' is the second slow-death movie to open here in as many days, and chances are it's about people who feel worse than you do. Here, as in ''Tribute,'' someone is mortally ill and trying to make sense of life while there's still time. Otherwise, there's no comparison between the two films, since ''Tribute'' is awash in false sentiment and ''Tell Me a Riddle'' is a slow, restrained, dignified effort. ''Tell Me a Riddle,'' which was directed by Lee Grant, opens today at the 68th Street Playhouse.

'EMPIRE OF PASSION'
description: EMPIRE OF PASSION,'' which opens today at the Public Theater, is the latest film by Nagisa Oshima, the Japanese director who three years ago startled quite a few people, including United States Customs inspectors, with the undisguised eroticism of ''In the Realm of the Senses,'' a movie whose two lovers carried their obsession with sex to an all-consuming conclusion. ''Empire of Passion'' is a far more gentle, infinitely more romantic, movie in which the obsession is not only sex but also the love that encompasses it.

description: TO a greater or lesser extent, all fiction is a study of human behavior. What distinguishes ''Mon Oncle d'Amerique,'' Alain Resnais's fine, funny new French comedy, is the film's mock-grave suggestion that human behavior isn't quite as mysterious as we like to pretend it is and that, indeed, most of the terrible things that happen to us need not be inevitable.

'MIRROR CRACK'D'
description: A THUNDERSTORM rages across the night landscape. Brief flashes of lightning reveal a great English country house, the sort inhabited by well-bred ladies and gentlemen who wear dinner clothes 24 hours a day and sometimes stoop to murder. Inside the house, in the drawing room, the assembled guests greet the newly arrived police inspector with apprehension. The inspector, not one to waste time, goes around the room, revealing, in turn, each person's awful secret, including the awful secret of the untrustworthy-looking butler with the big ears. Then, just as the inspector is about to tell all, the screen goes blank.

A SIMON COMEDY, 'SEEMS LIKE OLD TIMES'
description: ''SEEMS LIKE OLD TIMES'' is Neil Simon in very funny form, which is to say that the belly-laughs, while intermittent, are belly-laughs just the same. The cast is extremely appealing, and the director, making his feature debut, is Jay Sandrich. Mr. Sandrich, who directed many episodes of ''The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' is no stranger to appealing casts, and he hasn't much modified his television tactics to suit a feature film. He didn't have to. The material here is slick and entertaining, and Mr. Sandrich settles for comic simplicity without reaching for anything more. He coaxes the film along at a cheerfully breakneck rhythm.

description: IN the pretitle sequence that opens ''A Change of Seasons,'' Bo Derek, last season's sex symbol, is seen frolicking nude in a hot tub, photographed in the kind of slow-motion that allows the audience to admire virtually every perfect bubble and pore. Bo dives beneath the surface, immediately to emerge like some magnificent, anthropomorphic, submarine missile, radiant and dripping wet. Again and again she dives. Again and again she springs forth, renewed. She's a live-action Playboy centerfold. Then, unfortunately, the movie starts.

'THE JAZZ SINGER'
description: SOUND. Al Jolson. ''Mammy.'' These were three notable ingredients of the original version of ''The Jazz Singer,'' and, among them, only sound is present in the current remake, which stars Neil Diamond. The sound is a mixed blessing, since it allows for Mr. Diamond's often nondescript score, and for the rehash of a plot that makes not one bit of sense any more. Nevertheless, ''The Jazz Singer'' has the sloshy, melodramatic, show-biz appeal of something like ''A Star Is Born,'' which even in its latest, weakest incarnation managed to drag 'em in. This movie has nothing but foolishness to carry it along. At least it is foolishness that pretends, however unsuccessfully, to be grand.

'THE FORMULA' FOR SYNTHETIC OIL
description: AS Marlon Brando and George C. Scott, two tubby titans, square off for their final confrontation in ''The Formula,'' Mr. Brando utters the film's best line. This is it, in its entirety: ''Milk Dud?'' The rest of the dialogue has had to do with oil cartels and international intrigue. And it has been so convoluted that Mr. Brando's big moment - kind of a bonbon mot - works well not only because it's funny, but also because it's simple and clear. ''The Formula,'' which has at least as much to do with the price of tea in China as with its apparent subject - the price of oil on the world market - opens today at the Manhattan 1 and other theaters.

'BREAKER MORANT' ON THE MORALITY OF WAR
description: ''Scapegoats of the Empire'' is the title of a book by someone who survived the affair on which ''Breaker Morant,'' a new Australian movie with a dependably old-fashioned manner, is based. The drama takes place in 1901, in South Africa, at the end of the Boer War. The action is confined almost exclusively to a trial, the outcome of which is a fait accompli. The mood of it recalls military drama of the 1950's, like Terence Rattigan's ''Ross.'' In this case, the gears move almost automatically. There's nothing unexpected here, but neither are there omissions of anything an audience might anticipate. As based on Kenneth Ross's play, ''Breaker Morant'' is a shapely and orderly kind of drama. Its greatest strength is that it delivers what it promises.

'MAGICIANS OF THE SILVER SCREEN'
description: JIRI MENZEL, the Czechoslovak director of the Oscar winning ''Closely Watched Trains'' (1967) and ''Capricious Summer'' (1968), observes the world with the kind of skepticism that would distrust a sunrise already in progress. His movies aren't dark enough to be called pessimistic. Instead, they display a suspicion - strictly tentative, of course - that everything is not going to turn out all right. This is the center of his comedy, which is so fragile that it seems almost rude to laugh in its presence.

THALIA RESCUES 'PICTURE SHOW MAN'
description: ''PICTURE SHOW MAN,'' a 1977 Australian film now having its American premiere at the Thalia, is so chipper it positively chirps. Chronicling the adventures of pioneer movie exhibitors who travel from town to town unreeling silent films, it's a pleasant movie trying hard to be a merry one. Like many of the overlooked films the Thalia launches, this one demonstrates both the good intentions that justify unearthing it, and the lack of oomph that accounts for its previous obscurity.
